          "title": "Ten stands and basins — mobile worship-service",
          "body": "The ten wheeled bronze stands (7:27-39), each carrying a basin holding forty baths of water, are the chapter's most technically complex objects. The narrator devotes fifteen verses to their description — their dimensions, their panels, their wheels (made like chariot wheels, 7:33), their engraved decoration of cherubim, lions, and palm trees (7:29, 36). Five stands were placed on the south side of the Temple, five on the north, while the great sea stood at the southeast (7:39). The 2 Chronicles 4:6 account again supplies their function: the basins on the stands were for washing what was used in the burnt offering. The ten stands were thus the operational wash-stations for the sacrificial system — mobile (on wheels), numerous (ten), and beautiful (engraved with the iconographic program of sovereignty, strength, and life). The combination of mobility and ornamentation is theologically instructive: worship-service that is functionally efficient need not be aesthetically bare. God's house received what was both useful and beautiful — the false dichotomy between functional and ornamental was not allowed to govern the Temple's furnishing."
